english:
  title: Biography of Suseong the Monk
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There was a Buddhist monk named Suseong. He was from Hyeonpung County, where his family had dwelt for generations until his father Gyeon relocated the household to Haepyeong, where Suseong was born.

    When Suseong was but twelve or thirteen years old, he went to study letters under a monk at Hongbok Temple. Yet his nature was dull and sluggish. When his master expounded the dharma, the boy would merely parrot back the words; when the master fell silent, not a sound escaped his lips. Upon returning home each day, his father would have him recite what he had learned, but Suseong could remember only a phrase or two, forgetting the rest. Even what remained in his memory was muddled and unclear. Gyeon grew angry, saying, "Your two elder brothers have already proven themselves useless. You alone were my hope for this family's future. Must you disappoint me as well?" He beat the boy and instructed the monk to shave his head and take him as a disciple.

    By age twenty, Suseong studied Buddhist texts as before, yet with no greater success. Now properly garbed and capped as a layman, he fell into reverie—visions of clouds drifting far. He crossed the Nakdong River, passed below Mount Taebaek, climbed Fengwue to gaze upon vast waters, traversed the eastern regions, crossed the mountain passes, and sought out every renowned peak of the east. Yet the more wonders he beheld, the deeper his ignorance grew. At every temple where he dwelt, he was rebuked for shirking his duties.

    Eventually he came to Daeseung Temple on Four Buddha Mountain, where he underwent the summer retreat with thirteen monks. For three months he faced the wall in meditation, seeking to understand what is called "my nature." Is nature revealed in its function? Then it is merely vital force, not nature itself. Do all sentient beings possess it? Yet I and others differ in some way. He sought but could not find; found but could not perceive. All efforts bore no fruit. Fearing that his companions might disturb his mind and cloud his nature's clarity, he withdrew to meditate in solitude.

    With a fellow seeker named Hyeongmyeong, Suseong dwelt in Naeyang Hermitage in the southern mountains near Gyeongju. When Hyeongmyeong went out to gather rice, Suseong sat alone. At night, fierce tigers prowled the gate, their roars thundering so fiercely that the walls shook. Yet Suseong felt no fear; he sat firm as stone. His neighboring monks all witnessed this and understood that his peace arose not from supernatural power nor from desperate pretense, but from something deeper still.

    Through trials and hardships, worn thin and weathered, Suseong grew weary of monastic life. He came to see that the world's teaching of "seeing one's nature and becoming Buddha" was nothing but hollow fantasy. Casting off his restraint, he began to keep company with scholars and poets. When he heard the teachings of the sages on humanity and righteousness, and the wisdom of the classics, he felt as though light dawned within him. Though the old habits clung to him still, his aspiration was truly worthy. Many in the world follow such a path—they begin studying letters but, failing to succeed, don on the robes of a monk to appear noble; or they begin Buddhist practice but, unable to complete it, hide behind literature and sink into dissolution. Such cases are numberless as the sands; how could one count and condemn them all?

    When Suseong studied the Mencius under my tutelage, he came to the passage: "There are three kinds of unfilial conduct; the greatest is to have no posterity." He read it three times over, sighing deeply: "These words are indeed true. I am a criminal of the world." Ah, how deeply he had grasped the words of the sages; how clearly he perceived his former errors. This is why I have written his biography.

    Confucius said: "In teaching, we make no distinctions of kind." Mencius said: "When one returns, we need only receive him." Did Confucius and Mencius deceive me?
  footnotes:
    - Suseong's journey through Korea's sacred mountains—crossing the Nakdong River, passing Mount Taebaek, and climbing Fengwue (Mount Geumgang)—mirrors the spiritual pilgrimage of many East Asian seekers, representing both physical wandering and inner confusion.
    - The tiger at the cave door is a classic test of Buddhist meditation, appearing in many Chan/Seon tales as an emblem of fear overcome through cultivation.
    - The final citations of Confucius and Mencius signal Lee Cham's larger argument about redemption through classical learning—that the Way of the sages transcends sectarian boundaries and remains open to all who turn toward it.
